{"id":"2101.12213","submitter":"Payel Mukhopadhyay","authors":"Rebecca K.Leane, Tim Linden, Payel Mukhopadhyay, Natalia Toro","title":"Celestial-Body Focused Dark Matter Annihilation Throughout the Galaxy","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 103, 075030 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.103.075030","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE astro-ph.CO hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Indirect detection experiments typically measure the flux of annihilating\ndark matter (DM) particles propagating freely through galactic halos. We\nconsider a new scenario where celestial bodies \"focus\" DM annihilation events,\nincreasing the efficiency of halo annihilation. In this setup, DM is first\ncaptured by celestial bodies, such as neutron stars or brown dwarfs, and then\nannihilates within them. If DM annihilates to sufficiently long-lived\nparticles, they can escape and subsequently decay into detectable radiation.\nThis produces a distinctive annihilation morphology, which scales as the\nproduct of the DM and celestial body densities, rather than as DM density\nsquared. We show that this signal can dominate over the halo annihilation rate\nin $\\gamma$-ray observations in both the Milky Way Galactic center and globular\nclusters. We use \\textit{Fermi} and H.E.S.S. data to constrain the DM-nucleon\nscattering cross section, setting powerful new limits down to\n$\\sim10^{-39}~$cm$^2$ for sub-GeV DM using brown dwarfs, which is up to nine\norders of magnitude stronger than existing limits. We demonstrate that neutron\nstars can set limits for TeV-scale DM down to about $10^{-47}~$cm$^2$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jan 2021 19:00:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-05"}
